        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New Orleans</placeName>
                <date>March 1. 1854</date>.</p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev. I. Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Friend,</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">You will probably chide me for<lb/> not having sent you my little
                funeral address spoken<lb/> at the <add>?</add> of the late <persName>Mr.
                    Touro</persName>. The truth is I preferred<lb/> reading your own remarks, which
                I am fully assured,<lb/> will be more gratifying to your readers. The Asmonean<lb/>
                I perceive has published <persName>Clapp's</persName> sermon in full,<lb/> and a
                most wretched production of a rhymester<lb/> which, to save the credit of Jewish
                talent ought<lb/> to have been suppressed. What do you think<lb/> the author of it
                has even the ineffable conceit<lb/> to send it to <persName>Mr Shepperd</persName>
                and ask for his<lb/> patronage! And thus it has been a subject of<lb/> ridicule in
                the Picaynue<add>?</add> of this city.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Regarding the transmission of the<lb/> remains of your late
                venerable friend, <persName>Mr. G.<lb/> Kursheedt</persName> will no doubt have
                advised you.<lb/> It will not take place before <date>July</date> next.
                    <persName>Mr.<lb/> K.</persName> has the sole management of the whole
                affair;<lb/> a rather delicate duty is thus devolving upon<lb/> him. The question
                will not be, how much<lb/> shall be done, but how little of the num-</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>numerous resolutions adopted by various bodies<lb/> at the
                    <placeName>North</placeName> shall be carried into effect. There<lb/> can be no
                separate action allowed, and the prob-<lb/>ability is that, in endeavouring to give
                satisfaction<lb/> to all, <sic>offence</sic> may be taken in some quarter. I<lb/>
                shall be satisfied with whatever arrangements<lb/> will be made; tho' as yet I do
                not even know,<lb/> whether I shall be permitted to be present.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I am really sorry to hear you speak in<lb/> so despondent a strain.
                Is there nothing in your<lb/> present independent position to counterbalance
                the<lb/> unjust treatment you have experienced? Think<lb/> for a moment, you were to
                deliver a sermon “On<lb/> the disappointments incident to human life.”<lb/> Would it
                not be a principal point, to exhort your<lb/> hearers to courage and perseverance
                and to warn<lb/> them against despondency? You would probably say,<lb/> “As long as
                your heart is good and your intentions<lb/> are pure, you need not complain, nor
                fear.<lb/> The approbation of your conscience, and the coun-<lb/>tenance of the
                almighty, will preserve your in-<lb/>ward peace amidst the most
                    <sic>harrassing</sic> occur-<lb/>rences. Vain, hollow and thanging<add>?</add>
                is the applause<lb/> of man. Take it for what it is worth, fret not<lb/> when it is
                withheld, or bestowed on unworthy ob-<lb/>jects.” I am sure, you would present the
                subject</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>in such a light, and I am much mistaken, if<lb/> you do not apply the same sentiments
                to your<lb/> own case.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">We are anxiously awaiting the Bible. I<lb/> heard, that it is
                finished. Let us have it, therefore<lb/> at your earliest convenience. I hope the
                    en-<lb/><sic>terprize</sic> may be a profitable one, as it richly<lb/> deserves
                to be.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Hoping that this may reach you in<lb/> your good health and
                spirits</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">I remain</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <persName role="author">James K. Gutheim</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
